description: Launching Kealia on a good day with the Firefly
Back again after a month being grounded due to COVID19 Emergency Orders

Practice Makes Perfect

Camera: Joseph Turner
Canopy Pilot: Gage Galle
Wingsuits: Carson Klein, Scott Freeland, & TK Hinshaw
All footage was taken from two skydives made on Saturday morning, the 8th of September 2012.

North Shore, Oahu, Hawaii 07-Apr-2012

Conditions: Moderate-Strong 18-20mph winds with gusts up to 25mph

Synopsis: The Ozone Firefly is a new wing design produced by Ozone. It only comes in one size: 16m. I had the chance to demo the wing at another launch, but conditions were light and I didn't get a long flight; however, I decided to order myself a wing. 

After ground handling the new wing for awhile at a grass field I recognized that it acts vastly different from Ozone's Bullet class wings. It is an "unstable" wing meaning that it is more susceptible to input. In short: it is more fun to fly, but more difficult to handle on the ground. 

During my initial launch & flight I found that, as I expected, the wing indeed took more skill to launch than a bullet class wing, but once in the air it excelled in its ability to turn & maneuver. The wing has excellent forward speed for a 16m & great glide performance compared to a bullet class wing. 

One of the biggest lessons I learned on this first flight is to never hook the wing for landing as it causes to wing to gain altitude at a low angle of attack and then surge towards the ground, after reaching an apex, very lightly loaded with no flare. I then heard from a reliable source that it is advisable to do a slow carving turn rather than a fast hook turn for the reasons listed above. 

All in all I am happy thus far with the wing. I was very conservative during this initial flight, but I look forward to a slightly less windy day to take the Firefly up and unleash the wings true potential.

-TK Hinshaw
